  <h2>Step 2: GPS Service at Start-up <em>[update_gps.service]</em></h2>
  <p>To automatically run your script <code>/home/pi/scripts/update_gps.py</code> at startup on your Raspberry Pi, the most reliable method is to use a systemd service.</p>

  <h3>âœ… Step-by-Step: Create a systemd service</h3>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Create the service file:</strong><br>
      <code>sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/update_gps.service</code>
    </li>

    <li><strong>Paste this configuration:</strong>
      <pre>
[Unit]
Description=Update GPS Text File
After=network.target

[Service]
ExecStart=/usr/bin/python3 /home/pi/scripts/update_gps.py
WorkingDirectory=/home/pi/scripts
StandardOutput=journal
StandardError=journal
Restart=on-failure
User=pi       # CHANGE TO YOUR USER IF REQUIRED

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
      </pre>
      <p>Save and exit: <code>Ctrl+O</code>, <code>Enter</code>, then <code>Ctrl+X</code></p>
    </li>

    <li><strong>Enable the service to run at boot:</strong><br>
      <code>sudo systemctl daemon-reload</code><br>
      <code>sudo systemctl enable update_gps.service</code>
    </li>

    <li><strong>Start the service now (optional):</strong><br>
      <code>sudo systemctl start update_gps.service</code>
    </li>
  </ol>
</body>
